          "body": "Isaiah's oracle (vv. 21-34) is the chapter's theological center of gravity and one of the most dramatic divine speeches in all of Kings. It falls into three movements: a taunt against Sennacherib from personified Jerusalem (vv. 21-22), God's direct confrontation of Sennacherib's boast (vv. 23-28), and the promise of sign, remnant, and Assyrian withdrawal (vv. 29-34). The taunt section is remarkable: the 'virgin daughter of Zion' shakes her head behind Sennacherib in contempt — Jerusalem mocks the man who mocked the living God. The confrontation section (vv. 23-28) takes Sennacherib's first-person boasts ('I have ascended... I have cut down... I have dried up') and reframes them: 'Have you not heard? Long ago I did it; from ancient times I planned it' (v. 25). God is not responding to Sennacherib's power — He is revealing that Sennacherib's entire career was an instrument of His own pre-planned decree (cf. Isaiah 10:5-6, 'Woe to Assyria, the rod of My anger'). The chapter's most theologically dense claim is v. 25: Sennacherib's military conquests were not his achievement — they were God's ancient appointment, now rescinded."
